cs.SI, cs.CL, cs.SD, cs.CY, cs.CE

This paper involves the development of a semantic and linguistic framework to collect and analyze Twitter data related to public health opinions on diabetes, diet, exercise, and obesity. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) as it involves the analysis of social media data. The paper also involves natural language processing techniques to analyze the tweets, which suggests that it could also belong to cs.CL (Computation and Language). Additionally, the paper involves the use of statistical analysis to identify correlations between topics, which could place it in the sub-categories of cs.SD (Software Engineering) or cs.CY (Computers and Society). Finally, the paper involves the application of the framework to support clinical providers and public health experts, which could place it in the sub-category of cs.CE (Computers and Education).
